&= \frac{1}2 \begin{pmatrix}3 \\ 2 \\ -5\end{pmatrix}y + \begin{pmatrix}\frac{29}2 \\ 0 \\ -\frac{17}2\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}The direction vector of the line is $\begin{pmatrix}3/2 \\ 1 \\ -5/2\end{pmatrix},$ which we can clear denominators of to get $3\hat{\textbf{i}} + 2\hat{\textbf{j}} - 5\hat{\textbf{k}}$ as a direction vector for the line. Now let the normal vector of the plane the line is in be $\begin{pmatrix}a \\ b \\ c\end{pmatrix};$ then since the plane contains the line, the direction vector of the line and $\begin{pmatrix}a \\ b \\ c\end{pmatrix}$ will be perpendicular, so $\begin{pmatrix}3 \\ 2 \\ -5\end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix}a \\ b \\ c\end{pmatrix} = 3a + 2b - 5c = 0,$ or $3a = 5c -2b.$ Then the normal vector of the plane is $\begin{pmatrix}5c - 2b \\ b \\ c\end{pmatrix},$ and the plane going through $(1, 1, 1)$ with this normal vector is \[(5c - 2b) + b + c - 6 = 0,\]or $6c - b - 5 = 0.$ Now let $c = 1,$ which yields $b = 1$ and $a = 1,$ so the plane is $\boxed{\textbf{(A) } x + y + z - 5 = 0}.$</think> <answer> \textbf{(A) } x + y + z - 5 = 0 </answer>

